      Libor
   =20
 =20

Banks often raise money by issuing fixed-to-floating-rate  preferred stock:=
 They sell shares for $25, and for some fixed period (often five, seven or=
=C2=A010 years) those shares pay an annual dividend of, say, 6% ($1.50 per =
year, or $0.375 per quarter). And then after that they start paying a divid=
end that changes each quarter based on some benchmark interest rate. Usuall=
y the preferred stock is perpetual =E2=80=94=C2=A0the bank never has to pay=
 it back =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is callable: After it switches from a fixed =
to a floating rate, the bank can decide to pay it back at par ($25 per shar=
e). The rough idea is:
=09For the bank, this looks like perpetual preferred stock, which counts as=
 good loss-absorbing regulatory=C2=A0capital.=09For investors, this looks a=
 bit like a medium-term=C2=A0bond: The preferred is perpetual, but it only =
has five to 10 years of fixed-rate interest-rate risk; after that the bank =
will either call it, or it will pay a market-based interest rate and so sho=
uld trade fairly close to par.

For many years, the standard benchmark interest rate was Libor, the London =
interbank offered rate, and fixed-to-floating preferreds normally reset to =
Libor plus some fixed spread. =E2=80=9CLibor plus 4.0%,=E2=80=9D the contra=
ct might say, and then if three-month Libor was 3.0% on some quarterly rese=
t date, the dividend rate for that quarter would be 7.0% per year ($0.4375 =
for the quarter). (Technically this is a =E2=80=9Cdividend rate,=E2=80=9D b=
ut it is natural and common to call it an =E2=80=9Cinterest rate=E2=80=9D i=
nstead, since the preferred is a fixed-income instrument.)
A puzzle in issuing a stock like this is how to define Libor.=C2=A0
Libor=C2=A0was=C2=A0a rate determined by calling around a bunch of banks ea=
ch day and asking them how much they=E2=80=99d charge to lend money, unsecu=
red, for various terms and various currencies, to other big banks. The admi=
nistrator =E2=80=94=C2=A0for a long time it was the British Bankers=E2=80=
=99 Association =E2=80=94=C2=A0would do the poll and then publish a trimmed=
 average of the answers as Libor.=C2=A0
Traditionally in these contracts Libor would be defined something like this
  [1]
:
=09There is some Bloomberg or Reuters page that shows the BBA=E2=80=99s pub=
lished Libor rates, and =E2=80=9Cthree-month Libor=E2=80=9D is defined as t=
he interest rate (for US dollars and three-month maturity) displayed on tha=
t page, =E2=80=9Cor such other page as may replace=E2=80=9D that page.=09If=
 Bloomberg or Reuters no longer displays a Libor page, then Libor=C2=A0is g=
enerally defined as the result that you get by calling =E2=80=9Cfour nation=
ally-recognized banks in the London interbank market=E2=80=9D and asking th=
em for =E2=80=9Ctheir offered quotation for deposits in U.S. dollars for a =
period of three months =E2=80=A6=C2=A0to prime banks in the London interban=
k market at approximately 11:00 a.m. (London time),=E2=80=9D and then avera=
ging their quotes.=C2=A0That is, basically, if the Libor poll is no longer =
reported on a financial information service, the bank will=C2=A0re-create a=
 small version of the poll itself.=09If you can=E2=80=99t get any banks to =
quote a Libor-like rate, then =E2=80=9Cthe dividend shall be calculated at =
the dividend rate in effect for the immediately preceding dividend period=
=E2=80=9D: If there=E2=80=99s no Libor this quarter, you just use last quar=
ter=E2=80=99s Libor.

Well, there=E2=80=99s no Libor anymore. There was a big scandal a decade ag=
o =E2=80=94=C2=A0it turns out that when you ask banks what interest rate th=
ey pay, sometimes they lie =E2=80=94=C2=A0and regulators slowly got rid of =
it. Now there are other floating benchmark interest rates that are based mo=
re on market data; in the US the main one is SOFR, the Secured Overnight Fi=
nancing Rate, based on Treasury repo transactions. SOFR is a bit different =
from Libor =E2=80=94=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s overnight, whereas=C2=A0Libor was fo=
r longer terms, and it=E2=80=99s secured (by Treasuries), whereas Libor was=
 unsecured =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is like Libor in being the successor=C2=A0=
standard US dollar floating interest rate.
And there are all these contracts =E2=80=94=C2=A0floating-rate loans, bonds=
, preferred stocks, all sorts of things =E2=80=94=C2=A0that reference Libor=
. Some of these contracts were renegotiated as Libor went away: I owed you =
money at Libor plus 4%, Libor was going away, so we sat down to negotiate a=
 new floating rate. But many contracts were hard to renegotiate: A preferre=
d stock, for instance, is owned by lots of anonymous investors who can=E2=
=80=99t easily be contacted to agree to a new rate.
So, in the US, Congress and the Federal Reserve got involved. The very very=
 simple fix would be to just declare, by law, =E2=80=9Call references to Li=
bor now mean SOFR,=E2=80=9D but that would be economically wrong: Libor, be=
ing longer-term and riskier than SOFR, is higher=C2=A0than SOFR, so just re=
placing Libor with SOFR would lower everyone=E2=80=99s interest rates. The =
more reasonable but almost as simple=C2=A0fix would be to just declare, by =
law, =E2=80=9Call references to Libor now mean SOFR=C2=A0plus=C2=A0an adjus=
tment=E2=80=9D to reflect the fact that three-month Libor was a three-month=
 unsecured rate and SOFR is an overnight secured rate.
And Congress kind of did that? Last year it passed  the Libor Act, which sa=
ys roughly that:
=09If there is a contract that uses Libor, then Libor, in that contract, wi=
ll be replaced by a =E2=80=9Cbenchmark replacement=E2=80=9D chosen by the F=
ederal Reserve;=C2=A0except
=09If the contract has a =E2=80=9Cfallback provision=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0if it says something like =E2=80=9Cif there=E2=80=99s no Libor, we=E2=80=
=99ll use this other interest-rate benchmark=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0then t=
he contract will just use that fallback provision instead of the Fed=E2=80=
=99s benchmark.

And then the Fed  published regulations implementing that. And now =E2=80=
=9Cthree-month Libor=E2=80=9D means =E2=80=9Cthree-month CME Term SOFR plus=
 0.26161%.=E2=80=9D
Now here is a question. I laid out how typical bank fixed-to-floating prefe=
rred stock works:
=09The floating rate is a published Libor rate.=09If Libor isn=E2=80=99t pu=
blished, it=E2=80=99s a rate based on polling banks.=09If there=E2=80=99s n=
o Libor at all, the floating rate is the previous quarter=E2=80=99s rate.

Does that have a =E2=80=9Cfallback provision=E2=80=9D? Obviously Option 1 i=
s just Libor, and that went away. Option 2 =E2=80=94=C2=A0re-create Libor y=
ourself by polling banks =E2=80=94=C2=A0does not count as a fallback provis=
ion; the Libor Act says that =E2=80=9Ca requirement that a person (other th=
an a benchmark administrator) conduct a poll, survey, or inquiries for quot=
es or information concerning interbank lending or deposit rates=C2=A0shall =
be disregarded as if not included in the fallback provisions of such LIBOR =
contract and shall be deemed null and void and without any force or effect.=
=E2=80=9D
But Option 3? I mean, in a fixed-to-floating preferred, (1) there is a fixe=
d rate for five to=C2=A010 years and then (2) it=E2=80=99s Libor. If Libor =
goes away while the preferred is still fixed-rate, then, by pure mechanical=
 reading of the contract, that means that the preferred is fixed-rate forev=
er: After it becomes floating-rate, each quarter, you look at Libor, you ca=
n=E2=80=99t find a Libor, so the contract says that the interest rate for t=
hat quarter is the same as the previous quarter. Which is the fixed rate.
And so if you are a bank that issued a fixed-to-floating preferred in the l=
ast decade,=C2=A0when interest rates were low, and it will soon start float=
ing, and interest rates are high now, you might say, well, we have fallback=
 language, and the rate is fixed (and low) forever.
Here is  a fun story from Barron=E2=80=99s:

Welcome to the Twilight Zone of two preferred stocks from PennyMac Mortgage=
 Investment Trust (ticker: PMT), a real estate investment trust that invest=
s in mortgages (and no relation to government sponsored enterprise Freddie =
Mac). These two preferreds, series A (PMT.PRA) and series B (PMT.PRB), were=
 of the fixed-to-floating-rate variety. That means they paid a fixed divide=
nd until a specified time, after which their payouts would be adjusted base=
d on the London interbank offered rate, or Libor, plus a spread.
Based on that, PennyMac preferred-share investors likely anticipated a big =
rise in payouts next year. The series A preferred dividend was slated to ad=
just from 8.125% annually on March 15, 2024, to Libor plus 5.831%. The seri=
es B dividend was set to change from 8% to Libor plus 5.99%. Those changes =
would likely have put the preferreds' payouts over 11%. ...
But in a press release published late in the afternoon on the last Friday o=
f August, PennyMac announced that, per the contractual provisions for its p=
referred shares, the dividends would be fixed at the rate of the preceding =
period -- for series A and series B shares, 8.125% and 8%, respectively. Ha=
d PennyMac used a base rate of 5.56% (SOFR's 5.3% plus 0.26161%), that woul=
d produce a dividend rate of 11.39161% for series A and 11.55% for series B=
. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0
Adding insult to injury, the shares sank in the wake of the Aug. 25 dividen=
