   =20
 =20

The basic story is:
=09There is obviously demand for a Bitcoin exchange-traded fund, a thing th=
at you can trade on the stock exchange and hold in your brokerage account t=
hat gives you exposure to the price of Bitcoin. If you could make that, peo=
ple would buy it.=09The easy way to make that would be to create an ETF tha=
t holds a pot of Bitcoins, issues shares of the pot, and allows arbitrageur=
s to exchange Bitcoins for shares and vice versa. That is roughly the way, =
you know, stock and bond ETFs work, and it is good and straightforward.=09H=
owever, in the US, the Securities and Exchange Commission has adamantly opp=
osed this method =E2=80=94=C2=A0the spot Bitcoin ETF=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0du=
e to some combination of weird concerns about manipulation on crypto exchan=
ges=C2=A0plus, I think, a general philosophical desire not to make it too e=
asy for retail investors or traditional institutions to buy crypto.=09You n=
eed SEC approval to list a new ETF, the SEC has not approved any spot Bitco=
in ETFs, so there aren=E2=80=99t any in the US.=09So some people came up wi=
th a clever workaround,   the Bitcoin futures ETF, where they raise a pot o=
f money and use it to trade Bitcoin futures on regulated commodity exchange=
s. The ETF shares represent a claim on those futures rather than on a pot o=
f Bitcoin.=09That=E2=80=99s pretty good =E2=80=94=C2=A0the futures prices t=
rack Bitcoin prices pretty well =E2=80=94 though there=E2=80=99s some track=
ing error=C2=A0and it=E2=80=99s more expensive than just sitting on a pot o=
f Bitcoins.=09Crucially, the SEC has=C2=A0approved=C2=A0Bitcoin futures ETF=
s: They trade only regulated futures listed on US commodity exchanges, so t=
he SEC can=E2=80=99t really complain that their markets are manipulated.
  [3]

=09So there are, in the US, Bitcoin futures ETFs but not spot Bitcoin ETFs.=
=09Grayscale Bitcoin Trust, a pot of Bitcoins that is not an ETF, has sued =
the SEC, demanding that the SEC let it turn its pot of Bitcoins into a spot=
 Bitcoin ETF.=09Last month, Grayscale   won its case in court. It is not an=
 ETF yet =E2=80=94=C2=A0the SEC still has some cards to play =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0but it will =09probably become one.=09This is good for Grayscale (which =
gets to convert into an ETF), though it   has some downsides (fees for ETFs=
 are generally a lot lower than the 2% Grayscale charges).=09It is very goo=
d for other big ETF firms that can now get into the spot Bitcoin ETF game. =
BlackRock Inc., for instance,   has one in the works.=09It is very bad for =
the people who made Bitcoin futures ETFs. What a good idea they had! A clev=
er workaround to a regulatory impediment, something that let investors get,=
 like, 90% of the benefits of a Bitcoin ETF while threading the needle of S=
EC approval. In a world without spot Bitcoin ETFs, the Bitcoin futures ETF =
was a desirable product, though also something of a=C2=A0niche=C2=A0product=
; you were never going to get=C2=A0everyone=C2=A0comfortable with its compl=
exities. Still, good workaround. But more or less pointless now, if everyon=
e can buy a simple cheap spot Bitcoin ETF instead.

Bloomberg=E2=80=99s   Vildana Hajric reports:

