      Credit
   =20
 =20

For =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I want to say my entire career as an investment banker a=
nd then financial writer, there was a standard story about corporate loan a=
nd bond terms, and it went like this:
=09There were a lot of investors with a lot of money looking for yield, and=
 not that much yield available.=09Therefore, when companies wanted to borro=
w money, they had a lot of leeway to write documents (loan agreements, bond=
 indentures) that were favorable to them. Loans were often =E2=80=9Ccovenan=
t-lite,=E2=80=9D and the documents often allowed companies to do various tr=
icky maneuvers that would   disadvantage some creditors.=09Every so often l=
enders would notice, and complain, and push back, and sometimes even win =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0some of the most egregious terms proposed by borrowers were =
  rejected by the market =E2=80=94=C2=A0but broadly things were pretty=C2=
=A0borrower-friendly. Lenders would=C2=A0complain, but then they would=C2=
=A0lend anyway.

There are nuances to this story, and=C2=A0it is not a=C2=A0pure=C2=A0story =
about the macro environment. Borrower-friendly terms were also a matter of =
who was borrowing and who was lending: In recent years, in particular, a lo=
t of borrowing has been done by companies owned by sophisticated private eq=
uity firms who care a lot about maximizing their flexibility, and a lot of =
lending has been done by collateralized loan obligation managers who kind o=
f don=E2=80=99t care. But the basic story of =E2=80=9Cmoney is plentiful, l=
enders don=E2=80=99t want to miss out on deals, so they agree to weak terms=
=E2=80=9D had a good run.
But then rates went up and it ended? The Financial Times reports that =E2=
=80=9Ccredit hedge funds that focus on distressed debt are making bumper pr=
ofits this year as the rise in borrowing costs hits weaker companies,=E2=80=
=9D and it adds:

The tougher fundraising environment has given hedge funds much more negotia=
ting power to ask for interest rates of 14 per cent or higher, while buildi=
ng in tougher covenants to ensure they are repaid.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CI think this is a golden age for fresh credit because legacy credi=
t has a lot of flaws in it, not least a lack of covenants,=E2=80=9D said St=
uart Fiertz, president of London-based Cheyne Capital.
=E2=80=9CWe can come in with very good covenants and shape the transaction =
any way we like.=E2=80=9D

The broad story in credit markets for a long time has been that the borrowe=
rs shape the transaction, not the lenders. Not anymore. The broad story has=
 been that lenders make loans, but complain a lot about the terms. Now the =
lenders are positively bragging about the terms!

