10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Libor</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Banks often raise money by issuing fixed-to-fl=
oating-rate <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/326719=
30.258424/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucGltY28uY29tL2dibC9lbi9yZXNvdXJjZXMvZWR1Y2F0aW9uL=
3VuZGVyc3RhbmRpbmctcHJlZmVycmVkLXNlY3VyaXRpZXMjOn46dGV4dD1GaXhlZCUyRHRvJTJE=
RmxvYXRpbmclMjBSYXRlJTNBLG5vdCUyMGNhbGxlZCUyMGJ5JTIwdGhlJTIwaXNzdWVyLg/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB082bc2f5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> preferred stock</a>: They sell shar=
es for $25, and for some fixed period (often five, seven or=C2=A010 years) =
those shares pay an annual dividend of, say, 6% ($1.50 per year, or $0.375 =
per quarter). And then after that they start paying a dividend that changes=
 each quarter based on some benchmark interest rate. Usually the preferred =
stock is perpetual =E2=80=94=C2=A0the bank never has to pay it back =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0but it is callable: After it switches from a fixed to a floating r=
ate, the bank can decide to pay it back at par ($25 per share). The rough i=
dea is:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">For the bank, this looks like perpetua=
l preferred stock, which counts as good loss-absorbing regulatory=C2=A0capi=
tal.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">For investors, this looks a b=
it like a medium-term=C2=A0bond: The preferred is perpetual, but it only ha=
s five to 10 years of fixed-rate interest-rate risk; after that the bank wi=
ll either call it, or it will pay a market-based interest rate and so shoul=
d trade fairly close to par.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For many years, the standard benchmark interes=
t rate was Libor, the London interbank offered rate, and fixed-to-floating =
preferreds normally reset to Libor plus some fixed spread. =E2=80=9CLibor p=
lus 4.0%,=E2=80=9D the contract might say, and then if three-month Libor wa=
s 3.0% on some quarterly reset date, the dividend rate for that quarter wou=
ld be 7.0% per year ($0.4375 for the quarter). (Technically this is a =E2=
=80=9Cdividend rate,=E2=80=9D but it is natural and common to call it an =
=E2=80=9Cinterest rate=E2=80=9D instead, since the preferred is a fixed-inc=
ome instrument.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A puzzle in issuing a stock like this is how t=
o define Libor.=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/32671930.258424/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVz=
LzIwMjItMDEtMzEvbGlib3Itd2FzLW1hZGUtdXAtYW55d2F5P2NtcGlkPUJCRDA5MTEyM19NT05=
FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPT=
IzMDkxMSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBce89212d"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;">
Libor=C2=A0was</a><em>=C2=A0</em>a rate determined by calling around a bunc=
h of banks each day and asking them how much they=E2=80=99d charge to lend =
money, unsecured, for various terms and various currencies, to other big ba=
nks. The administrator =E2=80=94=C2=A0for a long time it was the British Ba=
nkers=E2=80=99 Association =E2=80=94=C2=A0would do the poll and then publis=
h a trimmed average of the answers as Libor.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Traditionally in these contracts Libor would b=
e defined something like this<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-=
1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !impor=
tant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">There is some Bloomberg or Reuters pa=
ge that shows the BBA=E2=80=99s published Libor rates, and =E2=80=9Cthree-m=
onth Libor=E2=80=9D is defined as the interest rate (for US dollars and thr=
ee-month maturity) displayed on that page, =E2=80=9Cor such other page as m=
ay replace=E2=80=9D that page.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If =
Bloomberg or Reuters no longer displays a Libor page, then Libor=C2=A0is ge=
nerally defined as the result that you get by calling =E2=80=9Cfour nationa=
lly-recognized banks in the London interbank market=E2=80=9D and asking the=
m for =E2=80=9Ctheir offered quotation for deposits in U.S. dollars for a p=
eriod of three months =E2=80=A6=C2=A0to prime banks in the London interbank=
 market at approximately 11:00 a.m. (London time),=E2=80=9D and then averag=
ing their quotes.=C2=A0That is, basically, if the Libor poll is no longer r=
eported on a financial information service, the bank will=C2=A0re-create a =
small version of the poll itself.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=
If you can=E2=80=99t get any banks to quote a Libor-like rate, then =E2=80=
=9Cthe dividend shall be calculated at the dividend rate in effect for the =
immediately preceding dividend period=E2=80=9D: If there=E2=80=99s no Libor=
 this quarter, you just use last quarter=E2=80=99s Libor.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well, there=E2=80=99s no Libor anymore. There =
was a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32671930.258=
424/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvTGlib3Jfc2NhbmRhbA/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cB4a76818d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;">big scandal</a> a decade ago =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
it turns out that when you ask banks what interest rate they pay, sometimes=
 they lie =E2=80=94=C2=A0and regulators slowly got rid of it. Now there are=
 other floating benchmark interest rates that are based more on market data=
; in the US the main one is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
com/click/32671930.258424/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubmV3eW9ya2ZlZC5vcmcvbWFya2V0cy9yZ=
WZlcmVuY2UtcmF0ZXMvc29mcg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB42bd5741" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">SOFR</=
a>, the Secured Overnight Financing Rate, based on Treasury repo transactio=
ns. SOFR is a bit different from Libor =E2=80=94=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s overnigh=
t, whereas=C2=A0Libor was for longer terms, and it=E2=80=99s secured (by Tr=
easuries), whereas Libor was unsecured =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is like Libor =
in being the successor=C2=A0standard US dollar floating interest rate.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And there are all these contracts =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0floating-rate loans, bonds, preferred stocks, all sorts of things =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0that reference Libor. Some of these contracts were renegotiated as=
 Libor went away: I owed you money at Libor plus 4%, Libor was going away, =
so we sat down to negotiate a new floating rate. But many contracts were ha=
rd to renegotiate: A preferred stock, for instance, is owned by lots of ano=
nymous investors who can=E2=80=99t easily be contacted to agree to a new ra=
te.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So, in the US, Congress and the Federal Reserv=
e got involved. The very very simple fix would be to just declare, by law, =
=E2=80=9Call references to Libor now mean SOFR,=E2=80=9D but that would be =
economically wrong: Libor, being longer-term and riskier than SOFR, is <em>=
higher=C2=A0</em>than SOFR, so just replacing Libor with SOFR would lower e=
veryone=E2=80=99s interest rates. The more reasonable but almost as simple=
=C2=A0fix would be to just declare, by law, =E2=80=9Call references to Libo=
r now mean SOFR=C2=A0<em>plus=C2=A0</em>an adjustment=E2=80=9D to reflect t=
he fact that three-month Libor was a three-month unsecured rate and SOFR is=
 an overnight secured rate.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And Congress kind of did that? Last year it pa=
ssed <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32671930.2584=
24/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY29uZ3Jlc3MuZ292L2JpbGwvMTE3dGgtY29uZ3Jlc3Mvc2VuYXRlLWJp=
bGwvMzc3OS90ZXh0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5810ae65" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the Libor Act<=
/a>, which says roughly that:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If there is a contract that uses Libor=
, then Libor, in that contract, will be replaced by a =E2=80=9Cbenchmark re=
placement=E2=80=9D chosen by the Federal Reserve;=C2=A0<em>except</em>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If the contract has a =E2=80=9Cfa=
llback provision=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0if it says something like =E2=80=
=9Cif there=E2=80=99s no Libor, we=E2=80=99ll use this other interest-rate =
benchmark=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0then the contract will just use that fall=
back provision instead of the Fed=E2=80=99s benchmark.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then the Fed <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/32671930.258424/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmVkZXJhbHJlc2V=
ydmUuZ292L25ld3NldmVudHMvcHJlc3NyZWxlYXNlcy9iY3JlZzIwMjIxMjE2YS5odG0/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cB4c81d0c4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> published regulations</a> implementin=
g that. And now =E2=80=9Cthree-month Libor=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32671930.258424/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubmV3eW9ya=
2ZlZC5vcmcvbWVkaWFsaWJyYXJ5L01pY3Jvc2l0ZXMvYXJyYy9maWxlcy8yMDIzL0FSUkMtc3Rh=
dGVtZW50LW9uLTEtMy02LTEyLW1vbnRoLVVTRC1MSUJPUi5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cBe87fa2a9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;">means</a> =E2=80=9Cthree-month CME Term SOFR plus 0.261=
61%.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now here is a question. I laid out how typical=
 bank fixed-to-floating preferred stock works:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The floating rate is a published Libo=
r rate.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If Libor isn=E2=80=99t pub=
lished, it=E2=80=99s a rate based on polling banks.</li>=09<li style=3D"mar=
gin-bottom: 5px;">If there=E2=80=99s no Libor at all, the floating rate is =
the previous quarter=E2=80=99s rate.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Does that have a =E2=80=9Cfallback provision=
=E2=80=9D? Obviously Option 1 is just Libor, and that went away. Option 2 =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0re-create Libor yourself by polling banks =E2=80=94=C2=A0doe=
s not count as a fallback provision; the Libor Act says that =E2=80=9Ca req=
uirement that a person (other than a benchmark administrator) conduct a pol=
l, survey, or inquiries for quotes or information concerning interbank lend=
ing or deposit rates=C2=A0shall be disregarded as if not included in the fa=
llback provisions of such LIBOR contract and shall be deemed null and void =
and without any force or effect.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But Option 3? I mean, in a fixed-to-floating p=
referred, (1) there is a fixed rate for five to=C2=A010 years and then (2) =
it=E2=80=99s Libor. If Libor goes away while the preferred is still fixed-r=
ate, then, by pure mechanical reading of the contract, that means that the =
preferred is fixed-rate forever: After it becomes floating-rate, each quart=
er, you look at Libor, you can=E2=80=99t find a Libor, so the contract says=
 that the interest rate for that quarter is the same as the previous quarte=
r. Which is the fixed rate.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so if you are a bank that issued a fixed-t=
o-floating preferred in the last decade,=C2=A0<em>when interest rates were =
low</em>, and it will soon start floating<em>, and interest rates are high =
now</em>, you might say, well, we have fallback language, and the rate is f=
ixed (and low) forever.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/32671930.258424/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmFycm9ucy5jb20vYXJ0aWNs=
ZXMvcmVpdC1wcmVmZXJyZWQtc2hhcmUtaW52ZXN0b3JzLW5hc3R5LXN1cnByaXNlLTJiZDUxNTN=
i/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB969558af" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> a fun story from Barron=E2=80=
=99s</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Welcome to the Twilight Zone of two preferred =
stocks from PennyMac Mortgage Investment Trust (ticker: PMT), a real estate=
 investment trust that invests in mortgages (and no relation to government =
sponsored enterprise Freddie Mac). These two preferreds, series A (PMT.PRA)=
 and series B (PMT.PRB), were of the fixed-to-floating-rate variety. That m=
eans they paid a fixed dividend until a specified time, after which their p=
ayouts would be adjusted based on the London interbank offered rate, or Lib=
or, plus a spread.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Based on that, PennyMac preferred-share invest=
ors likely anticipated a big rise in payouts next year. The series A prefer=
red dividend was slated to adjust from 8.125% annually on March 15, 2024, t=
o Libor plus 5.831%. The series B dividend was set to change from 8% to Lib=
or plus 5.99%. Those changes would likely have put the preferreds' payouts =
over 11%. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But in a press release published late in the a=
fternoon on the last Friday of August, PennyMac announced that, per the con=
tractual provisions for its preferred shares, the dividends would be fixed =
at the rate of the preceding period -- for series A and series B shares, 8.=
125% and 8%, respectively. Had PennyMac used a base rate of 5.56% (SOFR's 5=
.3% plus 0.26161%), that would produce a dividend rate of 11.39161% for ser=
ies A and 11.55% for series B. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Adding insult to injury, the shares sank in th=
e wake of the Aug. 25 dividend announcement: Series A fell 6.5% to $21.83 t=
his past Thursday, and series B dropped 5% to $21.67. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Market pros have been critical of PennyMac's a=
ctions, which differed from the vast majority of payers of floating-rate in=
struments that transitioned to SOFR from Libor. "PMT's behavior was particu=
larly nasty, even exploitative, to investors," wrote Charles Lieberman, chi=
ef investment officer of Advisors Capital Management, in an email. He's als=
o an investor in other mortgage REITs' fixed-to-float preferred shares.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Lieberman noted the PennyMac preferreds were $=
25 par issues traded on exchanges and aimed at individual investors. "I don=
't think they would have had the sheer chutzpah to treat institutional inve=
stors that badly, " he wrote. "I'm glad we had no exposure here, since I wo=
uld have been royally upset."</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know! The thing is, PennyMac<a=
 class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpa=
rent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0can=E2=80=99t just change the terms of its preferred stocks by it=
self. Either the Libor Act changed those terms (in which case PennyMac=E2=
=80=99s shares pay SOFR, plus=C2=A00.26161%, plus 5.831% or 5.99%), or it d=
idn=E2=80=99t (in which case they pay 8.125% or 8% flat). Apparently PennyM=
ac takes the view that the third option in its preferred stock =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0the rate stays fixed forever =E2=80=94=C2=A0is a fallback provision, and=
 so the Libor Act didn=E2=80=99t override it, so that=E2=80=99s what the pr=
eferred stock now pays. (Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/32671930.258424/aHR0cHM6Ly9wbXQucGVubnltYWMuY29tL25ld3MtZXZl=
bnRzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2VzL25ld3MtZGV0YWlscy8yMDIzL1Blbm55TWFjLU1vcnRnYWdlLUl=
udmVzdG1lbnQtVHJ1c3QtQW5ub3VuY2VzLUxJQk9SLVJlcGxhY2VtZW50LVJhdGUtZm9yLWl0cy=
1TZXJpZXMtQS1hbmQtU2VyaWVzLUItUHJlZmVycmVkLVNoYXJlcy9kZWZhdWx0LmFzcHg/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cB3aa9835f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the press release</a>, and here is t=
he original 2017 prospectus for the 8.125% preferred.) That strikes me as =
=E2=80=A6 probably=C2=A0correct? The contract says that, if Libor goes away=
, the rate stays fixed forever. Libor went away, so the rate stays fixed fo=
rever.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Casual examination of other fixed-to-floating =
preferreds=C2=A0suggests that PennyMac is not alone. A lot of banks did rep=
lace all their Libors with SOFRs along the lines of the Libor Act; here are=
 announcements from <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/32671930.258424/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubW9yZ2Fuc3RhbmxleS5jb20vcHJlc3MtcmVsZWFzZ=
XMvcmVwbGFjZW1lbnQtcmF0ZS1mb3ItdS1zLS1sYXctZ292ZXJuZWQtdS1zLS1kb2xsYXItbGli=
b3ItbGlua2VkLQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6422968d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Morgan Stanley</=
a>, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32671930.25842=
4/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYnVzaW5lc3N3aXJlLmNvbS9uZXdzL2hvbWUvMjAyMzA2MjM5MTA0MjcvZ=
W4vQ2l0aXplbnMtRmluYW5jaWFsLUdyb3VwLUluYy4tQW5ub3VuY2VzLVRyYW5zaXRpb24tb2Yt=
VS5TLi1MSUJPUi1saW5rZWQtUHJlZmVycmVkLVN0b2NrLXRvLVRlcm0tU09GUi1SZXBsYWNlbWV=
udC1SYXRl/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB94bb584b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Citizens Financial Gr=
oup Inc.</a>=C2=A0and=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.c=
om/click/32671930.258424/aHR0cHM6Ly9pci5yZWdpb25zLmNvbS9uZXdzLWV2ZW50cy9wcm=
