-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
"> announcement from State Street Corp.</a>=C2=A0from June. State Street ha=
s some fixed-to-floating preferred stock (and bonds) that were indexed to L=
ibor, and that will now, under the Libor Act,=C2=A0be indexed to SOFR. But =
it also has some that won=E2=80=99t be:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Each series of State Street=E2=80=
=99s Preferred Stock listed in Annex 3 to this press release is governed by=
 the terms of a certificate of designation (each, a =E2=80=9CCertificate=E2=
=80=9D) and will not transition to Three-month CME Term SOFR by operation o=
f law or otherwise. The Certificate for each such series specifies a fixed =
dividend rate (the =E2=80=9CDividend Rate=E2=80=9D) for a dividend period b=
eginning on a specified date (the =E2=80=9CCommencement Date=E2=80=9D), in =
each case as shown for each series in Annex 3 to this press release, if Thr=
ee-Month USD LIBOR cannot otherwise be determined as provided in the applic=
able Certificate. Given that the Commencement Date for each such series fol=
lows the LIBOR Replacement Date, the Dividend Rate for each series after th=
e applicable Commencement Date will be the applicable fixed rate specified =
in Annex 3 to this press release.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is, some of State Street=E2=80=99s prefer=
reds are in the same boat as PennyMac=E2=80=99s: They=C2=A0<em>currently=C2=
=A0</em>have a fixed rate (=E2=80=9Cthe Commencement Date for each such ser=
ies follows the LIBOR Replacement Date=E2=80=9D), so their current interest=
 rate doesn=E2=80=99t change due to the Libor Act. And when they=C2=A0<em>m=
ove=C2=A0</em>to a floating rate in the future, there is fallback language =
saying that, if there=E2=80=99s no Libor, they just use the previous quarte=
r=E2=80=99s rate. Which will be the fixed rate, forever.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Obviously PennyMac=C2=A0<em>could=C2=A0</em>ca=
ll the preferred stocks=C2=A0at their first call date in 2024. This would m=
ean paying investors $25 for shares that currently trade below $22. And the=
n PennyMac could=C2=A0replace them with new preferred stock that pays a hig=
her dividend rate, say SOFR plus 6%. That would be <em>nice</em>, for inves=
tors; it would give the investors roughly the experience (seven years of fi=
xed payments, then perpetual floating-rate payments) that they signed up fo=
r. But, you know, why? PennyMac has lucked into cheap(ish) perpetual financ=
ing, and it would be a bit silly to give it up.</p>
