<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic story is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">There is obviously demand for a Bitco=
in exchange-traded fund, a thing that you can trade on the stock exchange a=
nd hold in your brokerage account that gives you exposure to the price of B=
itcoin. If you could make that, people would buy it.</li>=09<li style=3D"ma=
rgin-bottom: 5px;">The easy way to make that would be to create an ETF that=
 holds a pot of Bitcoins, issues shares of the pot, and allows arbitrageurs=
 to exchange Bitcoins for shares and vice versa. That is roughly the way, y=
ou know, stock and bond ETFs work, and it is good and straightforward.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">However, in the US, the Securities and=
 Exchange Commission has adamantly opposed this method =E2=80=94=C2=A0the s=
pot Bitcoin ETF=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0due to some combination of weird concer=
ns about manipulation on crypto exchanges=C2=A0plus, I think, a general phi=
losophical desire not to make it too easy for retail investors or tradition=
al institutions to buy crypto.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You=
 need SEC approval to list a new ETF, the SEC has not approved any spot Bit=
coin ETFs, so there aren=E2=80=99t any in the US.</li>=09<li style=3D"margi=
n-bottom: 5px;">So some people came up with a clever workaround, <a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32671930.258424/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTAtMTUvYml0Y29pbi1ldGZ=
zLWFyZS1hbG1vc3QtaGVyZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwOTExMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPW=
VtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA5MTEmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduP=
W1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB45a684a3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  the Bitcoin <em=
>futures</em> ETF</a>, where they raise a pot of money and use it to trade =
Bitcoin futures on regulated commodity exchanges. The ETF shares represent =
a claim on those futures rather than on a pot of Bitcoin.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">That=E2=80=99s pretty good =E2=80=94=C2=A0the futu=
res prices track Bitcoin prices pretty well =E2=80=94 though there=E2=80=99=
s some tracking error=C2=A0and it=E2=80=99s more expensive than just sittin=
g on a pot of Bitcoins.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Crucially,=
 the SEC has=C2=A0<em>approved=C2=A0</em>Bitcoin futures ETFs: They trade o=
nly regulated futures listed on US commodity exchanges, so the SEC can=E2=
=80=99t really complain that their markets are manipulated.<a class=3D"foot=
note-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !importan=
t; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">So there are, in the US, Bitcoin =
futures ETFs but not spot Bitcoin ETFs.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: =
5px;">Grayscale Bitcoin Trust, a pot of Bitcoins that is not an ETF, has su=
ed the SEC, demanding that the SEC let it turn its pot of Bitcoins into a s=
pot Bitcoin ETF.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Last month, Grays=
cale <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32671930.2584=
