rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  rejected by the market=
</a> =E2=80=94=C2=A0but broadly things were pretty=C2=A0borrower-friendly. =
Lenders would=C2=A0<em>complain</em>, but then they would=C2=A0<em>lend any=
way</em>.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are nuances to this story, and=C2=A0it i=
s not a=C2=A0<em>pure=C2=A0</em>story about the macro environment. Borrower=
-friendly terms were also a matter of who was borrowing and who was lending=
: In recent years, in particular, a lot of borrowing has been done by compa=
nies owned by sophisticated private equity firms who care a lot about maxim=
izing their flexibility, and a lot of lending has been done by collateraliz=
ed loan obligation managers who kind of don=E2=80=99t care. But the basic s=
tory of =E2=80=9Cmoney is plentiful, lenders don=E2=80=99t want to miss out=
 on deals, so they agree to weak terms=E2=80=9D had a good run.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But then rates went up and it ended? The <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32671930.258424/aHR0cHM=
